name: Lampropeltis splendida (Baird & Girard, 1853)
occurrenceRemarks: Young adult male (Tyrosinase positive albino?) collected AOR on Hwy 90 3.2 miles W of Brackettville by Cam and Brenda Posey on 6/11/2010 @ 12:50 a.m. Pattern is consistent with area splendida (I have seen others from Highway 90 in the 1990s) and this type of albino is not represented in L. (g.) splendida in captive snake collections, thus it is not likely an escaped or released pet snake. The specimen was several years under my care (2015-2018) and acted like a wild snake as well (musking frequently even after years in captivity). It is still alive at these additional notes (May 2022) and has been bred by myself (first time in 2016) and Cam Posey producing six heterozygous offspring. None of those have been bred at this time. Map point is approximate.

verbatimLocality: Sunny Sands St, Chaparral, NM, US
name: Lampropeltis splendida (Baird & Girard, 1853)
Lampropeltis splendida (Baird & Girard, 1853)
occurrenceRemarks: Neonate barely missed by car in the oncoming lane. Curled into a ball thought for sure it had been hit. It uncoiled after photo and continued on its way. I'm going with Desert Kingsnake as I don't know if this is the vicinity or not for inter species relations? No other vouchers posted from this vicinity on Inat. Saw a DOR last year around the same mile marker (7). Also found another adult approx 6 miles to the East same road near the Devils Hwy.

name: Lampropeltis splendida (Baird & Girard, 1853)
identificationRemarks: Formerly Western Black Kingsnake, Lampropeltis getula nigritus. There seems to be a lot of fuss over this taxa, and I don't know when it was changed from Common to the Desert Kingsnake, but the lumping of this particular race in with Lampropeltis splendida seems a bit unclear (other than eliminating subspecies). I would not be surprised if it is ultimately determined to be its own species Lampropeltis nigrita or something similar so I am going with the Mexican Black given the option.

name: Lampropeltis splendida (Baird & Girard, 1853)
occurrenceRemarks: I saw this snake after midnight, in a sheltered construction ditch, during a mild rain storm. It did not seem afraid of me. I tried to take flash photos of it, and even flashing light did not cause the snake to move faster, or change direction. It was slowly exploring the dirt under a 4" pipe, and the soil around it, with its nose. With the pipe as a size reference, the snake was almost 2.5 ft long. It's skin was very smooth and dark. I saw no king snake-like spots or yellow, and I did not see a ring around it's neck.

name: Lampropeltis splendida (Baird & Girard, 1853)
occurrenceRemarks: DOR adult male 17 miles South of Fort Stockton. 78 degrees F. Recent rainfall. Dry road. Specimen not quite dead in image. GTS 4212. Sadly I did this. I would like to say that I found it already hit, however I was driving too fast and upon seeing it in the roadway (crossing from east to west) attempted to straddle it. Passing it I had the sinking feeling that I knew it was a desert kingsnake and that I probably did clip it. My highway speed was likely 50 mph. I turned around and found it as seen in the image. I collected the specimen (under permit) to deposit in a museum collection but would have much rather seen it crawl off into the desert scrub. I was traveling with my family and, while paying attention to the road, was not expecting this encounter.

occurrenceRemarks: Small rainstorm about two hours before sunset, which seemed to really stimulate activity this evening. Really unfortunate, this beautiful snake had been hit, and had a pretty large exposed wound. He was alive and moving, but behaving very unusually. I doubt he survived, unfortunately. Really a shame, lovely snake I was very excited to see. My lifer Socorro County

occurrenceRemarks: Looking for a storm cell to block the nearly full moon. The 90 just North of Lordsburg put on quite the show. Unfortunately I pulled this hatchling L splendida off the road after getting his head clipped. Saw several other snakes moving around the storm.
